Item_Response: Many things contributed to the growth of the population in the U.S. During this time period, the 1800s, there is a significant change in the amount of people,coal production, railroad tracks, and newspapers delivered in the United States.            During the 1800s, working people who could build, farm, or invent came to America in ship after ship. In the new technology, there was plenty for then to do. Germans were the largest single group of immigrants in the 1800s. Next to the Germans, the Irish were the largest immigrant group. One fourth of the whole population of Ireland came to America (that was 1.7 million Irish people). Later people from Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary came to avoid hunger. Others came for religious freedom.             The second half of  the 1800s was a time of great change. Industries grew and transportation improved. Once the first rail road was completed, it was easier to move resources and people's trips became shorter and easier. The invention of the telegram and telephone only made news travel even faster. The reasons are characterized as 'pushes' and 'pulls'. Pulls are those features that attract people. They include jobs, wealth, opportunities, access to resources, and perceived freedom. Pushes are those features in life that drive people from their homes. They include harsh environment, wars, conflicts, and poverty.               Lots of Chinese people moved to California because of the gold rush in 1849. More than 70,000 hopeful adventurers arrived in California in 1849. Among these 'Forty-Niners' were 325 men from China. More Chinese came next year, and the next. They hoped to find a fortune waiting for them. The first wave of Chinese came from Guangdong, an area in China's south coast. The Chinese called California Gam Saan or 'Gold Mountain.' By 1870, there were 63,000 Chinese in the United States.               As you can see, there were many things that contributed to the growth in population of the U.S. These included, the pushes, the gold rush, the improvement in transportation, and the new technology. This was a significant time period in history because of the huge increase in the population of the United States.

Item_Response: In the 1800's, life was difficult in many countries, which is why so many immigrants moved to the United States. But immigrants moved here for a good reason.                                                              In other countries, life was much harder. There were food shortages, and higher birth rates. When they came to America, though, there was plenty of work. The word got around, and people started pouring in.      People also moved to escape wars. They caused an unsafe and unpredictable lifestyle and home. Others came for freedom. Whether it was religious or not it still promised a happy and free life for many.        Some immigrants came to America to find opportunities and wealth, such as gold. The promise of riches was to great an opportunity to pass by.                                                  When transportation improved, it just made traveling easier. It was easier, faster, and cheaper to travel by steamship. Which meant more immigrants. The printing press made printing newspapers and books cheaper. The invention of the telegraph and telephone made news travel that much faster. And people come in that much faster. Which isn't necessarily a bad thing. There were plenty more jobs now.                       Without immigrants, America wouldn't be the melting pot, with all the different cultures, races, and heritages, is is today without them.

Item_Response: The 1800's was the start of major population and industrial in America. The 3 main reasons the 1800's was the start of major population and industrial growth in America is because people needed to move out of crowded countries escape hunger, gain religious freedom, and to have a chance to get rich.           One reason people move into America was because the countries they were living in were too crowded. The European population had doubled between 1750 and 1850. Europe couldn't handle all the people the had back then. They couldn't proved enough food or jobs for everyone. So, many of them moved to America.          Another reason people moved to America was to gain religious freedom. These people were often some German, Polands, and Russians Jews because they were mistreated in what they believed in by there home country. Russian Jews left to America to escape the risk of pogrom(organized violent attacks).          The last main reason people moved to America was to 'strike it rich'. In 1849, news about the California Gold Rush spread to China. About 325 Chinese men came to mine for gold. Most of the Chinese came from Guangdong to flee from conficts between China and Britian. At the time, Guangdong was getting too much people and not enough rice, so they moved. Most of them got gold and returned to China.          In conculsion, the 1800's was a time of major population and industrial growth in America. People came to escape crowded countries and hunger, while others came to gain religious freedom. But in the end, The 1800's was a time of change in America.

Item_Response: Why people came to America                                       Have you ever wondered why people came to America? If you do, then this article will answer your question.               According to the article of 'moving to America', one reason is that they came because they wanted to avoid hunger. The Irish were desperate because there crops had failed especially the potato crop. There was a food shortage. more than 1 million people died of starvation in Ireland.Int the 1800 people started coming to America people form Russia,Italy,Poland,Denmark,Sweden, and Hungary. The population of Europe doubled between 1750 and 1850. All those extra people needed food,homes,and jobs, and there just didn't seem to be enough for them in Europe.              In the article 'Gold Rush! Chinese move to California' it says people also came to America because they wanted to find gold. Gold was discovered in 1848 along the American River in California, on the property of a man named John Sutter. John Sutter tried to keep it a secret but the word spread and soon reached San Francisco,  and hundreds of people left the city to set off for the American River. The news spread to the rest of the United States, and to the other parts of the world as well. By January of 1849, 60 ships and thousands of overland travelers were headed to California. The California Gold rush had begun.            In ' Changes in America : The pushes and pulls for immigrants'it says people came to America to escape harsh conditions. Russian Jews left to escape prejudice and persecution, in the form pogroms, organized violent attacks. Southern Italians suffered from high birth rates and farming losses due to lower prices  the tradition of leaving family land to the first-born male often left younger siblings landless.Hungarians, Greeks, Poles, Portuguese, and Armenians also moved. Immigrants hoped to make a new life foe themselves and there family in the United States.             Those are some reasons why people came to America. I told you that people came to avoid hunger, that People came to look for gold, and that they came to escape harsh conditions.

Item_Response: Over 60 million people came to the United States between 1860 and 1910. These people came because of hardships in their country, opportunities in America, and of Americas modern technology. The United States is a country that many people immigrated to and this is why.         Many people immigrated to the United States because of hardships. For example, Russian Jews came from Russia to escape prejudice and persecution, in the form of violent attacks. These people came to America to be safe from harm. In addition, Southern Italians suffered from high birth rates, since the traditions was to give land to their first born son, it left many peoples children landless. These people came to America for their children to have a better life. Also, many Europeans came to America to escape conflict and poverty brought on by over crowding. These people came to America to have a better life for themselves and their children. This is the many hardships immigrants faced before they came to America.          In addition to hardships, many people came to America because of opportunities. To show this, people came to America for jobs. Many Europeans came to America to find work, since over crowding in Europe lead to job 'shortages'. Furthermore, people came to America to avoid hunger. A food shortage in Ireland killed 1 million people from starvation. People used that as a wake up call to move to a better place with more food. Finally, people saw  an opportunity in resources. People packed up their belongings and came to America for more resources for them and their families. A great number of people immigrated to America because of opportunities.         Finally, people immigrated to America because of the new technology in America. For example, from 1860 to 1910 over 200,000 miles of railroad tracks were layed across America which meant for easy travel . In addition to railroad tracks, Over 2,200 newspaper were delivered daily from 1860 to 1910. People found that new technology and the printing press made it easier to get news in America. Lastly, people came to America because of the new technology in factories. Jobs were needed in these factories and immigrants were ready to work. People came to America to get their hands on this new technology.         In conclusion, many immigrants came to the United States between 1860 and 1910. The hardships in their own countries 'pushed' them here, the opportunities and new technology 'pulled' immigrants to come live in America. America was a very promising country to the people between 1860 and 1910.

Item_Response: America, the land of freedom, is an amazing place to live in the 1800's and a great place to live now. It is a free country and provided many jobs in the 1800's. America gives immigrants a chance to start over, give them a new start on life. Its the land of opportunity.                 Immigrants had not much to do in the old country but immigrating to America would change that. There were a lot of new inventions and many jobs. Many new factories were being built which provided many jobs. Also crops grew and gave farmers a chance to get a job. The 1800's was also a big time for inventing. There were many crops for immigrants to farm and to plant crops. Ireland had a record high for immigrants in the farming community. Over one fourth of Ireland's population left to America to farm. (Hakim)              As much as immigrating is good  it also has the down turns. Just like a ball goes up it also must come down. These are the pushes and the pulls of immigrating to America. For example pulls are the things that attract people in life such as transportation grew and made resources easier to access. Also the telegraph was invented so now people could communicate easier and faster. But there are pushes in life also or what drive people away like the poverty in Europe. Also wars and other harsh conflicts. Many things in Europe 'pushed' them away and new technology 'pulled' people to America.             The Gold Rush was happening in the 1840's which attracted the Europeans and the Chinese. By 1849 many people were on their way to America to find gold. Over 60 ships set sail and thousands of travelers were already on their way. The nickname for these gold miners were the 'Forty-Niners'. Many people, especially the Chinese, came to hope to find a fortune in the Americas. More than 70,000 people with high hopes landed on the coast of California. The Gold Rush was a big attraction for many travelers.             Although there are many upturns and downturns the Europeans and Chinese made. They may have had a lot of trouble but they made it through. They provide crops, found gold, and made factories. Immigrants are a big part of America society and helped very much.

Item_Response: Today I am going to tell you about immigrants in America, Changes in America, and the Gold Rush.              First, I am going to be talking about the immigrants in America. During the 1800s, working people who could build, farm, or invent came to America in ship after ship after ship. With all the new technology in the 1800s there was plenty for them to do. Immigrants were needed to work in the new factories, to farm and build on the land, and to invent things. Germans made up the largest single group of immigrants in the 1800s. Irish men, women, and children kept coming, during and after the war. In the later 1800s, people started coming from other European countries that had not sent many people to America before. In total, some 26 million immigrants arrived in the United States over a 50 year period.                 Next, I am going to talk about Changes in America. The second half of the 1800s was time of the great change in America. Industry grew and many immigrants arrived on America's shores. Transportation improved and the first railroad that crossed the United States was completed in 1869. A trip to America in earlier times would have taken months, but the new steamships could make the trip much faster. Steam power and the redesign of the printing press made it possible to print many inexpensive books and newspapers. People became more interested of the world around them and with the ability to travel long distances easily, they moved are more than ever before.                 Finally, I am going to talk about the Gold Rush! Gold was discovered in 1848 along the American River in California, on the property of a man by the name of John Sutter. John tried to keep it a secret but word soon spread to San Francisco, and hundreds of people left the city to set off for the American River. More Chinese came the next year, and the next. Most of this first wave of Chinese migrants came from Guandonb, an area on China's south coast. In the middle of the 1800s, Guangdong was involved in two wars between China and Britain. The Chinese government raised taxes. Farmers who we're unable to pay their taxes had to sell their land. Guangdong's population was growing quickly. The area could not produce enough rice to feed its people, especially when the the floods destroyed the crops.                  In conclusion, the 325 Chinese who joined the gold rush in 1849 were just beginning. The next year, 450 more Chinese arrived in California. Then all of a sudden they became a greater number: 2,716 in 1851 and 20,026 in 1852. Although they could be found throughout the country, 77 percent of them were in California.

Item_Response: In the 1800's, many people decided to migrate to America. Germans had the largest group of immigrants. The Irish were the second largest group. Other immigrants came from Europe, Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary. Why did they migrate? There were many reasons like shortage of food, better crops, jobs, and freedom. there are many different reasons. Many people wanted to come because of all America had to offer, but some were almost forced. Living conditions in some countries made their lives difficult. To try to improve those conditions, they migrated.       In these times, one big thing was farming. People from Ireland mainly migrated due to farming. Many of their crops had failed, especially the potato crop. This was a big deal because if the crops died, then they would have no food for their families. More than 1 million people died of starvation. Before the war in the 1860's, a part of Ireland migrated to America. There was about 1.7 million Irish people at the time. They kept coming during and after the war. Later in the 1800's, European countries started sending people to America. This included Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary. Before they migrated, the population of Europe almost doubled to 1,800. They all needed food, homes, and jobs. There was not enough for everyone. They then migrated for jobs and to avoid hunger. Greeks, Portuguese, and Armenians also migrated hoping for new lives for them and their families. People even came because America had religious freedom. People from Holland and Jew who were from Germany, Poland, or Russia. Jews were often hurt or arrested for their beliefs. They figured they would at least have a chance here in America. In total, 26 million immigrates had come to America in a 50 year period.       In the 1800's, America had many improvements. They called these 'pulls'. They are features that attract you to people and to socialize. Transportation was a big deal once it improved. They had just created the first railroad. This made it easier to transport resources like silver and lumber from West to East. People were also allowed to travel on the trains. Traveling was now faster and easier. Later there ere trains that could take people straight to boats. Transportation improved even more when the steamship was invented. Migrating to America would usually take months, but now the trip was much faster. News was hard to get around. In 1844, the telegraph was invented. This just made the news travel faster. America really improved over the years!       Although migrating to America helped a lot of people, there were, however, challenges. They called these 'pushes'. These included rough environments, wars, poverty, and other problems. These conflicts worsened once the population in Europe increased. Europeans left due to harsh environments. Russian Jews escaped from prejudice,  persecution, and violent attacks. Southern Italians faced high birth rates and farming loses because of lower prices.       In 1848, gold was found along the American River in California by John Sutter. Although he tried to keep it a secret, it soon got out to the people of San Francisco. Many of them left to go to the river. It later spread through the rest of America. By the beginning of 1849, thousands of people were taken by ship to the river. The California Gold Rush had begun. More than 70,000 hopeful adventurers, called the 'Forty-Niners', which had 325 Chinese men among them. This may have seemed like a 'pull', but was also a 'push'. Soon the Chinese government raised taxes which made farmers have to sell their land because they could not pay for it. The population had started growing quickly. Soon they could not produce enough rice to feed the people, especially when it flooded. Many Chinese people joined the Gold Rush. This helped fix the problems.

Item_Response: Different immigrants migrated to America so they could escape from there country or state like the Irish men, women, and children who left Ireland because the crops were failing especially the potato crops and they were starving some even died from starvation.       Most Europeans came to find jobs and escape hunger while the Jews came to escape Germany,Poland,and Russia who mistreated the Jews beliefs in their home countries. Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary are some of the countries that left for America so they could have a better home at America. Most newcomers knew very little about America except that it was a land of freedom. But that's what they wanted: freedom and a chance to work.       Many of the new European immigrants wanted to escape harsh conditions in Europe. Russian Jews left to escape prejudice and persecution, in the form of pogrom-organized violent attacks. Southern Italians suffered from high birth rates and farming losses due to lower prices. Some Hunagarians, Greeks, Poles, Portuguese, and Armenians are some of the others who left for America. Immigrants hoped to make a new life for themselves and families in the United States.       Gold was discovered along the American River in California at 1848 on property of  John Sutter. He tried to keep the gold a secret but word got out that there was gold in the American River. By January of 1849, 60 ships and thousands of immigrants were headed for California. The Gold Rush had begun! More than 70,000 hopeful adventurers arrived in California in 1849 for the Gold Rush. Among these 'Forty-Niners' were 325 men from China.       Some of these Chinease immigrants were fleeing from conflicts and poverty. In the middle of the 1800s, Guangdong was involved in a war between China and Britain. The 325 Chinease who joined the gold rush in 1849 were just the beginning. The next year the Chinease arrived in California. Then suddenly they came in great numbers:2,716 in 1851, and 20,026 in 1852. By 1870, there were 63,000 Chinease in the United States.

Item_Response: New Life in America          In the 1800s, working people who build, farm, invent came to America in ships. There was a lot of new technology in 1800s so there was plenty for them to do. Lots of them were needed in factories, to farm and build on land, and to invent things.          Germans were the largest group of immigrants in 1800s, then the Irish. Before the American Civil war started, one-fourth of the whole Irish population came to America. Which means there were 1.7 million Irish men, women, and children. Many Irish were desperate, there was a food shortage.       Later in the 1800s, other people from European countries started to arrive in America. Including Sweden, Italy, Denmark, Poland, Russia, and Hungary. All of those people needed food, homes, and jobs.And mostly to avoid hunger.       Others came for religious freedom, such as Holland and Jews from other European countries. Still others came to escape wars, that made their lives harmful, and unstable.       26 million immigrants came to the United States over a 50 year period! They came for a chance of freedom, and a change in their lives.                                       Pushes and Pulls       The first railroad that crossed America was completed in 1869, this meant that resources would lumber form the West, to East. People would travel on these trains too, it made one trip from one place to another easier and faster.       People became more aware about the changes and world around them. With the ability to move along distances easily, they took advantage of it. Most reasons why they moved often were ' Pushes' and 'Pulls.' Pushes were things that drove people away, like harsh environment, wars, and other conflicts. Pulls were things that attracted people, for example: jobs, wealth, opportunities, and perceived freedoms.       Many of the new Europeans immigrants wanted to escape the horrible conditions in Europe. Southern Italians wanted to escape their sufferment from high birth rates and farming losses due to the low prices. Greeks, Poles, Hungarians, and Portuguese also moved. They ( As well as other immigrants ) hoped to make a better living for their families and themselves in the United States                                              Gold Rush!       There are a lot of pulls for the immigrants as may already know, but one of the most biggest pulls for the immigrants was the California Gold Rush! Many of the Chinese moved to join the California gold rush. The gold was discovered in 1848 along the American River in California. The property was owned by John Sutter, even though Sutter kept the secret to himself, the word spread to San Francisco and once the new spread all over the United States, and to other countries all over the world, hundreds of people left the city to go join the gold rush!         More than 70,000 hopeful adventures came to California in 1849. Among of these Forty-Niners were 325 for China! More Chinese came year after year! The Chinese hope they find some fortune in the California hills.

Item_Response: Moving to America                 Moving to America is very difficult, but can be very fortunate once you get there. America is full with new jobs, different religions, different languages, and much more exciting things.             In the 1800s, there were many immigrants that came from all over the world. Some came from Poland, Germany, Ireland, Russia, Italy, Denmark, China, and a lot of other places.             People came to America for freedom, wealth, a new environment, a new life, to escape wars, jobs, opportunities, avoid hunger, crops, and other things.             Wealth was one thing that brought very many people to America. For example, in 1848 there was a big gold rush in California. A big amount of people from China came to the gold rush. One year after another, the population of the Chinese going to the U.S. raised higher and higher. Many people from China came to find many different things, but 77% of them were in California.              Another reason why there were so many immigrants coming were because of people getting out of wars or fights. People were coming to find a new life, without violence. People from China came to America to get away from conflicts and poverty. China had 2 wars against Britain in their country. No one wants to live through that! China also had rebellions against their own government! Or they had village or family fights! Who in their right mind would want that in their village? Those are a couple reasons of why the Chinese came to America. Also, when they came to America, they got what they wanted!        People also came because they couldn't pay taxes or their bills. Farmers who couldn't pay their taxes had to sell their land. Where are we going to go? the farmers thought. The only place they could think of was America. They got their land and were happy with it. Item_Response: Immigration           Migrating from one country to another is very difficult. There are many advantages and disadvantages for moving to another country. Some advantages are that your country might have a food shortage so you could move to a different country that doesn't have a food shortage, there might be a really bad disease going around that's deadly and you wouldn't want to get it, or there might be a better job opportunity. Some disadvantages are: moving to a different country could be hard because you would have to sacrifice leaving family and friends, finding a job or a way to get money, not knowing the same language as the people in the country that you moved to, transportation, or the different time and climate changes that your body isn't used to. Now, lets see how people in the 1800s managed to do this, and why.       In the 1800s, many people migrated to America. There were many reasons why they did. Some did so that they could build, farm, or invent new things. The largest group of immigrants were the Germans, and then the Irish. Many of the Irish people migrated to America just before the Civil War, there was about 1.7 million families that came at this time. They came because there was a food shortage in Ireland so people were dieing. Many other countries came to America for this reason as well. Some other people came because of there religious beliefs[the Jews] because they were mistreated because of what they believed in.       In the later 1800s, America started to have many changes. Many things started to improve, and many more things were invented. Transportation improved, the telephone was invented,and printing books and newspaper became less expensive. Then, in the mid 1800s, gold was soon discovered.  In the next year people from everywhere around the United States and other countries heard about it and soon went to California for gold. This is when the Gold Rush began.       So, this is how and why immigrants migrated to America in the 1800s. For gold, jobs, because of prejudice people in there country, and many other reasons. So, now we know why all this happened!

Item_Response: Why People Moved to America in the 1800s               Although immigrating groups to the United States was a difficult journey in the 1800s, many people uprooted themselves and moved here. People had different reasons, but these are the main reasons they moved all over the globe to the U.S.A specifically.            Before the American Civil War in the 1860s, 1.7 million+ people came to America before and after the war. The Irish were desperate because their crops failed and because they had a food shortage, a million people died of starvation. In the later 1800s, European countries that hadn't sent many people to America before kept on coming to America. The population doubled in Europe. All the extra people needed food, homes, and jobs so they came to America because Europe didn't have enough. Other people from Holland, Poland, Russia, and Jews from Germany came for religious freedom. In total, twenty six million immigrants arrived in the United States over a fifty year period.            The second half of the 1800s was a great time of change for America. Industry grew and many new immigrants arrived on America's shores. Transportation improved, like the first railroad that crossed the United States was completed in 1869. So people can move to places faster. Item_Response: Many people have immigrated to America over the past decades. People from Germany, Ireland, Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary were some of the many immigrants who came to America hoping to seek a new life. Immigrants came for the land, food, people, jobs, or maybe even just to get away from disasters.       In the 1800s, the two largest groups of immigrants who came to America were from Germany and Ireland. Next to the Germans, the Irish were the largest immigrant group, one-fourth of the people from Ireland came to America. They kept coming during and after the Civil War. In the later 1800s, more people from Europe arrived to America to find work and to avoid hunger. Other immigrants came for religious freedom like the Jews.       The second half of the 1800s was a time of great changes for America. Industry grew and many immigrants arrived. American transportation improved after the first railroad was built. It became easier to travel and to ship resources to other places. There was also a rapid change in how quickly messages traveled. Steam power and the redesigning of the print press made it possible to print books and newspapers. The invention of the telegraph in 1844 and the telephone in 1876 was also a big improvement.       In 1848 gold was discovered along the American River in California and hundreds of people set for the American River. By January, ships of thousands of travelers were heading for California.   Many of the people hoping to strike it rich were Chinese immigrants. By 1870, there were 63,000 Chinese in the United States but 77% of them were in California.       Many immigrants have traveled to America in the 1800s. But that doesn't mean that there won't be anymore. More immigrants will travel to America and our technology will improve.

Item_Response: There many information about when, why, and how immigrants from other countries came to America. I would like to recognize stories of immigrants who immigrated over the last 200 years. Several facts and information will be explained why immigrants immigrated to America in the following article.        During the 1800s, many immigrants immigrated to America to escape slavery, finding opportunities, and religious cultures. Before the American Civil War in the 1800s, one fourth of the whole population of Ireland came to America. Ireland crops had failed, especially potato crops, which caused more than one million people starve. In the later 1800s, people started to come to America to find jobs, avoid hunger, find homes, and find opportunities. Other immigrants came for religious freedom that included Holland and Jews. In total, over  26 million immigrants arrived in America over a 50 year period. This information would explain why immigrants immigrated to America.        The secong half of the 1800s was a great time in America because their industries grew and many immigrants arrived in the U.S. As industries improved, transportation improved as well. Many workers completed the first railroad that crossed the United States at 1816, which caused to attract many immigrants to travel to America. Also, this meant that it was easier to move food stocks, lumber, and other resources. Travelers now could catch a train to America or ride a boat. Soon the population of America rapidly changed and widely information traveled. Steam power was soon invented and the printing press made it possible to print inexpensive books. Then, people became aware that they could get jobs, wealth, opportunities, and develop resources. Some immigrants fro Europe wanted to escape harsh conditions and moved to America. Russian Jews left there homes to  escape prejudice and persecution. There are much more reasons why immigrants immigrated to America, but these some main reasons why.        Soon, gold was discovered in 1848 along the American River in California by John Sutter. Sutter kept his discovery a secret, but the word soon got out that gold was discovery. Other parts of the world found out that gold was discovered in San Francisco in California, so people quickly reached California to find wealth, which caused the Gold Rush. The Gold Rush was mostly involved with the Chinese. The Gold Mountain stories were spread throughout China and caused the Chinese to join the Gold Rush. As the Chinese arrived at California, the population of California increased by 77% and most of them were Chinese. When time passed, the population of America multiplied from 1860 to 1910 and as a result about 92,407,000 people lived in America at 1910. In the following years people wondered how immigrants ended up living in America, well these are some reasons why they are.        In conclusion, many immigrants had different reasons why they immigrated to America, well they may wanted freedom, wealth, or even jobs. As conclude my essay on why immigrants immigrated to America, people had tough choices to go through whether immigrating to another country or staying.

Item_Response: Party in the U.S.A.              Many immigrants came to the United States in the 1800s, but why? They came because of pushes and pulls, or things that forced them to come, and things that lured them into coming. The pushes and pulls include harsh conditions and the finding of gold. Lots of immigrants came to the United States for these reasons!              One push reason causing immigrants to come to the United States were caused by of harsh conditions in Europe. Russian Jews left to escape 'organized violent attacks.' Italians went through harsh farming losses due to lower prices. Even the tradition of giving the land to the first baby boy was a mistake, since it left younger siblings landless! Hungarians, Greeks, Poles, Portuguese, and Armenians also moved, hoping to make a new life for themselves and their families in the United States. Europeans experience harsh conditions in the 1800s.              A pull reason that attracted people was gold. After gold was discovered in 1848 by John Sutter, it attracted huge amounts of immigrants. 70,000 hopeful adventurers came to California in 1849, and 325 of those men were from China. More and more Chinese came as the years went by, hoping to strike rich. Due to this event, by the 1870s, there were almost 65,000 Chinese in the U.S. What makes it even more amazing is the fact that there were only 2,716 in 1851. Gold clearly attracted immigrants.              As you can see, immigrants settled in the United States by pushes and pulls. The Europeans were forced to by harsh conditions, while the Chinese were attracted by the chance of sudden wealth. People in the United States need to be thankful for these events, for without them, where would we be without them?

Item_Response: I think that the immigrants moved to the United states in the 19th century for many reasons. There were things people wanted to be a part of, and also things they were trying to escape. America was seeming better and better by the day!               Some people came here to escape from harsh conditions in their home country. For instance, as it says in 'Moving to America' by Joy Hakim, 'The Irish were desperate because in Ireland crops had failed, especially the potato crop.' This was starving the Irish people, so many of them came here for food. But food was not the only problem. From the same article, 'Others came for religious freedom. These included people from Holland and Jews who came from Germany, Poland, and Russia.' Many of the people moving here were mistreated in their home countries and came for freedom.               Other immigrants came here to seek wealth and happiuness. To quote an excerpt from a book on immigrants by Ronald Takaki 'Gold Rush! Chinese move to California,' 'Like the people who came from the eastern United States, the Chinese hoped to find a fortune waiting for them in the California hills.' Many people looking for money came here to California for the gold rush. Not only the Chinese, but '70,000 hopeful adventurers' settled down in California during this time.               Still more people just wanted to get a taste of everything going on in America. It helped that 'The invention of the telegraph in 1844 and telephone in 1876 only made news travel faster.' ('Changes in America: The 'Pushes' and 'Pulls' for Immigrants') There was now news about everything great in America travelling at high speed everywhere. 'The second half of the 1800s was a time of great change in America.' Who wouldn't want great change? America is starting to pull ahead insustrially, and everyone else wants a part of it.

Item_Response: During the late 1800s many people left for America. People from all over the world came to live in The United States of America. Over 1.7 million people from Ireland left their homes to live here. There was about 200,000 more tons of coal produced in 1910 than in 1860. Between the years 1860 and 1910 America grew; a lot.           Between 1860 and 1910  travel was easier along with many other things. There were about 8 times as many miles of railroad tracks. This shows that there was a big improvement in the ease of traveling. This is important because if travel didn't get easier the west coast might not be American territory. About 9 times the number of daily newspapers existed. This shows that printing got a lot easier. This is important because, there would probably be less papers today if printing didn't get easier.       The gold rush made America grow, in a big way. The gold rush brought many people to California, 'more than 70,000 hopeful adventurers arrived in CCalifornia in 1849.' This shows that this helped the USA grow. Item_Response: American Immigrants      By: Kacie Bellisch             During the 1800s people from different country's came by ship.This was called immigration. Transportation would be improving day by day. The even started to build a railroad that crossed the United States and was completed in 1869. News traveled by the telegraph made in 1844 and the telephone made in 1876.         In 1848, gold was discovered along the American River in California. Item_Response: Cultural Heritage of the European Immigration       During the last 200 years, there was a big immigration. The Europeans built a boat to migrate to America. The Europeans wanted to migrate to America because they knew they would have a better life. Also, some of the Europeans came for freedom, religious freedom, foods and crops. Germans made up the largest single immigrant group in the 1800s. Next to the Germans, the Irish were the largest immigrant group. Before the American Civil War in the 1860s, one-fourth of the whole population of Ireland came to America. (That was 1.7 million Irish men, woman, and children.) they kept coming, during and after the war. The Irish were so desperate because in Ireland, crops had failed, especially the potato crop. There was a food shortage. More than 1 million people died of starvation in Ireland. In the later 1800s, people started coming from other European countries that had not sent many people to America before. This included Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary. The population of Europe doubled between 1750 and 1850.             Next, there was great a change in America. Industry grew and many immigrants arrived on America's shores. Transportation improved. The first railroad that crossed the United States was completed in 1869. This meant that it became easier and easier to move resources like silver and lumber from the West to the East. People could travel on these trains too. A trip from one place to another became shorter and easier for many people. A trip to America in earlier times would have taken months, but new steamships could make the trip much faster. These advances in transportation made it possible for more people to travel more easily.            Gold was discovered in 1848 along the American River in California, on the property of  a man named John Sutter. Although Sutter tried to keep the discovery a secret, word of the find soon reached San Francisco, and hundered of people left the city to set off for the American River. The news spread to the  rest of the United States, and to other parts of the world as well.  By January of 1849, 60 ships and thousand of overland travelers were head for California. The California gold rush had begun. More than 70,000 hopeful adventures arrived in California in1849. Among these 'Forty-Niners' were 325 men from China. More Chinese cam ethe next year, and the next. Like  the people who came from waiting for them in the Califoria hills.

Item_Response: Immigration to America in the 1800's       Imagine yourself in Europe, it is 1850, and many people including you and you family are in need of food and a job. What would you do? Many people decided to move to America.   Many people immigrated to America in the 1800's including people from Europe, China, and other countries. They came for a variety of reasons, such as promises of food, shelter, jobs, freedom, hope, and after the Gold Rush started, some came to find gold.       The Europeans made up a  very large group of the immigrants coming to America in the 1800's. Europe's population doubled between 1750 and 1850, so many were in need of food, shelter, and jobs. An Article called Moving to America by Joy Hakim states that many Europeans moved to America to Avoid hunger.   Those were not the only reasons why they moved to America, though. Some came to seek religious freedom. Some of these people included the Jewish people, who came from Germany, Russia, and Poland. They were often times discriminated and mistreated for their beliefs and religion.       Another group of people who came to America in the 1800's were the Chinese. They mainly kept their eye on California, where they hoped to get rich after the Gold Rush started in 1849. As it says in the article Gold Rush! Chinese Move to California, the Chinese called California Gam Saan, or 'Gold Mountain.' They heard about all the gold that was found there, and they craved to go to 'Gold Mountain', find a fortune, and return to China with their riches. According to the same source, 77% of the 63,000 Chinese  who lived in America in 1780 were living in California.   Some other reasons why the Chinese came to America could be to escape the oppressive government and the extensive village and family fights. In the mid-1800's, Guangdong was also involved in two wars between Britain and China.       The industry grew and transportation was improved in America in the second half of the 1800's. The first railroad to cross the United States was completed in 1869, and that meant resources such as silver and lumber could become more widely available. The redesigning of the printing press, steam power, the telegraph, and the telephone also helped information travel more quickly and widely. These things attracted immigrants too.       As you can see, many people from China and Europe emigrated from their own countries and went to America for with their own reasons; from seeking religious freedom to finding gold. The number of  people born outside the United States who were living there went from just over four million to over thirteen million from 1860 to 1910, just a fifty year period! America was the target for many people seeking a new start in the 1800's.

Some people wasn't even given that much food, because of their skin color, or because their planting went wrong.     Around the 1800s Irish people were desperate for food, that is because their crops have failed, they didn't grow or anything.   More than 1 million people died by starvation.     European countries had little things for people. Like food, they didn't have enough for everyone to get a whole meal. They couldn't get a home so fast, they had to do many certain things to be able to have a house. And jobs, not everyone had jobs. Kids didn't go to school or anything.     Some people didn't get to choose their religion because of they're skin color, or because the government didn't approve that. If they decided to choose their own religion, they would get beaten or killed.    Over a 50 year period, 26 million immigrants arrived in the United States. The newcomers only knew a little bit about America. But they knew it was a land of freedom because that's why they wanted to go there.        In 1869, the United States finished their first railroad, so it was much easier for them to move resources, like silver and lumber.   It was also must easier for the people to travel, because they can go in trains. It was easy for the people to go to one place to another.    It was also easy for Europeans to travel because there was a train that will take them right to a boat.    In 1844 the telegraph was invented, and in 1876 the telephone only made the news travel faster.   It was much easier for the people now, they had the ability to move long distances. These were often called 'pushes' and 'pulls'. 'pushes are those features of life that drive people from their homes' Like the harsh environment, war and other problems like that. They pushed their self to accomplish those things, even if it causes death.    'Pulls are those features of life that attract people.' Which is talking about jobs, wealth, access to resources, and of course perceived freedoms. People often pulled them self in doing those things because they didn't like how they been treated. They didn't like how they get beaten to death if they didn't do what their ruler said, or how they would die because they didn't get much food.    Most people in the European countries mostly wanted to escape, because a lot of people were suffering and they didn't like that.           Italians suffered by high birth rates, and farming loses. 'The tradition of leaving family land to the first-born male often left younger siblings landless.' The immigrants hoped to make a new life and have a family in the United states so they traveled to America.        'Gold was discovered in 1848 along the American River in California, on the property of a man named John Sutter.' John tried hiding the discovery a secret but the word went around fast. And a lot of people left their homes to travel to the American River to be rich. By January 1849, 60 ships were heading to California. That's when the gold rush had begun.    For China, if the people couldn't pay their taxes the Chinese government will raise their taxes. For the people that wouldn't be able to pay their taxes, the people would have to sell their land. The area couldn't even produce enough rice to feed the people. Especially because floods often happened, and their crops got over flooded and failed.    The news about the Gold Mountain was spread around China and many people wanted to join to become rich.    In 1849, 325 Chinese joined the gold rush. Item_Response: Many people moved to America in the 1800s. For example, according to the text, there were plenty of things to do in America. Like, people who came to America could've worked in factories, invented new things, and farmed or built on the land. So, there were many things to do in America that brought lots of immigrants to it.          The Germans made up the largest single group of immigrants in the 1800s. Next to them were the Irish. The Text directly states that, 1.7 million Irish men, woman, children came to America. That is one-fourth of the whole population of Ireland! During the Civil War, many people kept coming, during and after the war. For example, according to the text, the Irish were very desperate. A reason for this is because in Ireland many crops had failed, especially the potato crop. Also there was food shortage. A huge amount of people died in Ireland (over 1 million people) because of starvation.          Also, later in the 1800s, people started coming from European countries. Many people in Europe needed food, homes, and jobs. And there wasn't enough of those things in Europe. These people included Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary. So, many people from Europe came to the America to find work and to avoid hunger.           Many others came for religious freedom. This included people from Holland, Jews from Germany, Poland, and Russia. The Jews were often mistreated in their home countries so they came to America. Also, others came to escape wars.         In conclusion, 26 million immigrants arrived in the United States over a 50 year period. Many people arrived here because America was a land of freedom. Also, others came here for a chance to work and get money. So, many immigrants came to America for freedom, a chance to work, and get money.

Item_Response: Immigration Explanatory Performance Task       In the 1800s, people who could build, farm, or invent came to America in ship after ship. With their new technology, there was plenty of work they could do. they were needed to work in the new factories, farm, build on land, and invent things. The immigrants did it all.       Most immigrants moved more than ever because of what they call 'pushes' and 'pulls.' A push are the features of life that drive people from their homes. They include harsh environments, wars and other conflicts and poverty. A pull are the features of life that attract people. these include jobs, wealth, opportunities, access to resources, and perceived freedoms.       Many of the European immigrants wanted to escape harsh conditions in Europe. Russian Jews left to escape prejudice and persecution, in the form of Pogroms. Southern Italians suffered high birth rates and farming losses due to lower prices. The tradition of leaving their family to the first-born male often left younger siblings without land. Hungarians, Greeks, Poles, Portuguese, and Armenians also moved. The Immigrants hoped to make a better life for their families and themselves in the United States.       Chinese immigrants lived in poverty and conflict in their country. The Chinese were rebellious against the goverment. Also, they had endless village and family fights. The Chinese government raised taxes. Farmers who were not able to pay their taxes had to sell their land. The population in Guangdong was growing quickly and the area could not produce enough rice to feed its people. Especially when floods destroyed the crops. The people felt hopeless and they listened of the tales of gold over the Pacific Ocean. They longe to go their to make their fotunes and proudly return to China.

Item_Response: Moving to America in the 1800's   Written By: Tricia Happel                In the 1800's many people immigrated to the America's. Some of these people included: German's, Irish, Russian's,Italians, Pole's, Denmark's, Swedish, Hungarian, Jews, Holland, Greek's,  Portuguese, Armenians, and Chinese. There were 'pushes' and 'pulls' to come to America.As you can tell, America was a growing country!         Germans then Irish were the 2 largest immigrant groups. They were coming because of war,failing crops,food shortages,and starvation.America had plenty of good soil for these people because most of it hadn't been used yet. They couldn't starve and die with all of the food being grown.Later in the 1800's, European countries were sending people that hadn't before. All of these people coming needed: jobs, food, and shelter. There was lots of undeveloped land that could be used to put up shops and even makes houses.          Other immigrants were coming to find religious freedom. Mainly Jews, because they were mistreated for their religious beliefs in their countries. Life that was unstable made many others move to America.About 26 million people came to America in near 50 years!Many saw America as a land of freedom and opportunity.            Gold Rush! Gold Rush! Read all about it! In 1848 John Sutter discovered gold on his home estate in California. Since he found all of this gold, news spread around. Many Chinese moved to California searching for gold. Most of the Chinese came from Guangdong, trying to get away from poverty and war conflicts. And even many rebellions against the government, and raised taxes.Once they struck gold, and collected it, they went back home.             There were multiple reasons people moved to America. Like, searching for gold, religious freedom, food, shelter,etc. America made hopes and dreams for many people, but not everyone got what they wanted.By 1970 ,63,000 Chinese moved to the us, so imagine how many total people moved to America-that's a lot! From 1860-1910, 60,874,000  people moved to America! Now we now how important America was to people without many opportunities.

Item_Response: During the 1800s, working people who could do various things came to America in ships. With all the new technology there was plenty for them to do.   The Germans and the Irish came in the largest groups. Before the Civil War, one-fourth of the Irish population came to America. They kept coming to America, even after the war, because their crops had failed, even the potato crop, causing a food shortage. More than one million died of starvation in that period of time.   In the later 1800s, more immigrants came from all over countries in Europe, such as Russia, Iraly, Sweden, and other countries. Many Europeans came to America to find work and avoid hunger.   Others came for religious freedom.   In total, about 26 million immigrants arrived in the U.S. over a 50 year period.   In the second half of the 1800s, transportation improved. The first railroad that crossed the United States was completed in 1869. It made it easier to move resources like lumber and silver from the East to the West. People could travel by trains too. Taking a trip by train made traveling shorter and easier for many people.   People discovered that steam power and the redesign of the printing press made it possible to print inexpensive books and newspapers. The invention of the telegraph in 1844 and telephone in 1876 made news travel even faster.   Gold was discovered along the American River in California in 1848. Although the people of the discovery tried to keep it a secret, word got around very fast, starting the California Gold rush.

Item_Response: In the 1800's, people came to the U.S. because for food,   religious reasons, harsh conditions, wars, jobs, and much more. Here's why certain groups of immigrants moved to America.   Around 1860 in Ireland, a lot of crops didn't grow, resulting in   food shortage. Irish people came to America because of this and after that kept coming. Later on in the 1800's, people from Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary came to the U.S. because of need of food, houses, and jobs that there wasn't enough of in Europe. The people who didn't come for jobs, homes, or foods, came for religious reasons or to escape horrible wars.   A lot of Europeans wanted to get away from harsh conditions   in Europe so they came to America. Russian Jews escaped in pogroms from prejudice and persecution. Italians in the south had high birth rates and farming loss because of lower prices, which caused them to start their lifes over in the U.S.   In 1849, tons of Chinese people came to the U.S. to find gold   that had been found a year earlier. But some Chinese came because of problems with wars and poverty. People rebelled against the government. There was endless village and family fighting. Their government raised taxes, which caused farmers not able to pay them have to sell land. During all of this in Guangdong, China, the population was growing rapidly and the area couldn't grow enough food to give the people since the crops were getting flooded.   Of course all of this immigration caused the population to   increase. In 1860 the population was 31,513,000. By 1910 the population had almost tripled to 92,407,000. But the population wasn't the only thing to increase. The number of people who lived in cities in 1860 was more than 6 million and by 1910 was almost 42 million! The number of people born outside of the U.S. in 1860 was a little over 4 million and was up to 13 million in 1910. The coal collected in 1860 was almost 20.5 million tons. In 1910 more than 417 million tons was collected. That's more than 6 times the amount collected in 1860!! The miles of railroad track in 1860 was 30,626 and 240,293 in 1910. The number of daily newspapers in 1860 was 387 and was up to 2,600 in 1910. All of these things increased a lot in 50 years- and a lot of it was because of immigrates!

Item_Response: Immigration to America               Anybody who has moved to America from another country will know how difficult, but worth it, coming here was. There is a lot of freedom and natural resources found here that are not found in other countries.Most people moved from the late 1700s to early 1900s.Many people love this country.            There are many reasons why people moved here.These reasons are called  'pulls'.There are also reasons why people left their homes.These reasons are called 'pushes'. People leave for both of these things.                Immigrants came to America for various reasons.They left their homes because they wanted freedom and a chance to work.For example, the Irish left their homes in the 1800s because they were desperate because in Ireland farm crops failed and there was a shortage of food.According to an excerpt from A History of Us, more than 1 million people died of starvation in Ireland during this time period.  In European countries people from other countries moved there.  Because all those extra people needed food,  there wasn't enough to feed everyone.Many Europeans came to America to find work and to avoid hunger.I got this information from A History of Us.Others came in search for religious freedom.These included people from Holland, and Jews from Germany.                 There were also many 'pulls' that attracted people to move to America.Many of these pull reasons are jobs,wealth (The Gold Rush in 1848), opportunities, access to resources, and perceived freedom.According to American Population and Industrial Growth, 1860-1910, a chart from the Bureau of the Census, the number of people born outside of the US were 4,096,753 in 1860 , that increased to 13,344.545 people in 1910.These were allot the people who came to America in the second-half of the 1800s,wanting the new technology that was being manufactured at this point in history.                       As you can see, many immigrants suffered the consequences of leaving their homeland, but gave it all up for the freedom of this proud country called America.

Item_Response: In the 1800s Germans moved to America and found all this new technology, if they needed to work in factories, to farm and build land, even inventing things. Immigrants could do all of that. Germans were the largest group to immigrate to the U.S. in the 1800s. The second largest group is the Irish, one/fourth of the whole population came to get away from war. That's 1.7 million Irish men,women,and children. They kept coming, during and after the war. In he later 1800s people from Europe started immigrating to the U.S. People from Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary also came to the U.S. around this time. All of these European people needed food, homes, and jobs, because there wasn't enough in Europe.                                                               The second half of the 1800s was a time that everything changed in America. Americas industry grew and many more immigrants arrived on America's shores. One of the first railroads that crossed the united states was completed in the 1869. This made it easier to move resources like silver and lumber from the West to East. Having this railroad also made it easier for people to travel to far distances and make the tip shorter. If you want to take a train right to a boat you can and the trip wouldn't be as long as it would have been without the railroad. A trip to America in the earlier times the trip would have taken a very long time, but no with all the technology the trip would have been much much faster.                                          In the 1800s, there was also a rapid and important change in how quickly an widely information traveled. Now with a steam power and the redesign of the printing press made it possible to print many inexpensive books and newspapers. This made news and ideas available to more people. The telegraph invention in 1844 and the telephone in 1876 made news travel faster. With the ability to move long distances fast and easily, people moved more than ever before. The reason why they are moving more than ever is because of  'pushes' and 'pulls'.  Pushes are those ways of life that kick people out of their homes. those reasons include harsh environments, wars, and many other conflicts, and poverty. Pulls are the features of life that attract people, such as, jobs, wealth, opportunities, access to resources, and perceived freedoms.

Item_Response: Immigration Stories                For Cultural Heritage Day, my school is recognizing the stories of how the immigrants arrived to America. Immigrants came to America for many reasons. Some were 'pushed' to America by conflicts and harsh enviroment; while others were 'pulled' to America by the religious freedom and many  jobs. I would like to explain how these immigrants came to America and their stories.        Imagine this: you are a German child living in a world with harsh weather, no religious freedom, and tons of conflict. Your family cannot take your country anymore and decides to leave Germany for America. In this situation you are being 'pushed' to America. Irish immigrants were 'pushed' from their country due to crops failing and a shortage of food. After that, many other Europeans left to go to America so they didn't die of starvation. Other immigrants also left for religious freedom because America was known as the land of freedom. Some immigrants left their home countries to escape the war and find jobs. Over fiftey years 26 million immigrants were in the US. A majority of the immigrants were 'pushed' to America.        Imagine this: you are living in China, when word comes to you that in America there is riches beyond your belief. You pack your stuff and buy the next ticket to America, the land of freedom. In this case, you are being 'pulled' to America. Many immigrants left for America because of all the oppourtunities to become famous and rich. At this time, most of the inventors were immigrants. Famous scientist, Albert Einstien was an immigrant from Germany searching for a job. Many of the Chinese sailed to America because of the gold rush in California. Other immigrants left for jobs to support their family. Lots of immigrants were 'pulled' by America's jobs and riches.        After reading this passage you will be able to understand why immigrants came to America and their stories. When immigrants came the population flourished and the amount of production blasted up. Before immigration, not a lot of people were born outside of America, but after immigration a majority of the population was born outside of the US. I think immigration truley made a majoe impact on the united states.

Item_Response: Moving to America              People moved to America in the 1800s for a few reasons. One of the reasons was, there was the California Gold Rush. Many people from China decided to immigrate to America for gold.               Another reason people moved to America is, transportation improved. The first railroad in the United States was completed in 1869. This made it easier to transport resources such as, silver. These trains and other new transportation made it easier for people to transport things and to travel easier.                The new print press design made more print books and newspapers less expensive. This made people more aware of news and ideas in the United States.                  Another reason people immigrated to the United States in the 1800s is, there was much more new technology, factories, farms, and to invent things such as, the telephone. Some people immigrated to the United States because they were trying to avoid leading to starvation.                    Some people even came to the United States for religious freedom. America was known as the land of freedom. They came because what they wanted was, freedom and work. They needed a chance to work. They also came to America for coal production.                     Some people came to America because their crops failed and there was a food shortage. Some people came for homes. Some people came to America to escape wars that led them to an unstable life.                      A lot of people came for wealth, and opportunities. They would have better access to resources and harsh conditions. They also came so they wouldn't have violent attacks. They all came for a new life for family and themselves in America in some way.

Item_Response: In the 1800's, many people moved to America to find work, freedom, and many other reasons.  Others, like the gold rush, were used for greed and pride, not for survival.  In this paper, I will talk about why the immigrants came, for good or bad.            Many people from all over the world came to America during the Civil War and before.  Over all, the Germans made up the largest single group of all of the immigrants in America.  Right behind them, was the Irish. In the 1860's, one-fourth of Ireland's entire population came to America right before the Civil War.  SO many of them came because the crops in all of Ireland had failed, especially the potatoes.  Of the ones that didn't come to America, the three-fourths, 1 million men, women, and children died of starvation at that time.              Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary, all European countries, sent many people to America.  Before that, the population of Europe had rapidly increased, almost doubled, between the years of 1750 and 1850.  All of those people needed food, homes, and jobs, which were running very low. And that's how it all started.             In 1790's America was known as a brand new country. So, people took advantage of that. By the 1800's Immigrants were coming by ship loads, looking for jobs and money. The largest group of immigrants were Germans. Then There were the Irish. The Irish came to America because they were desperate for fertile land. Potato crop failed, so they decided to grow them somewhere else, so they came to the new land. LAter  in the 1800's other races of people came. Soon enough, every kind of person from Europe came to America. Russian, Italian, Polish, and others came to America. Item_Response: Imagine you live a life of poverty in the 1800s, and you find out that you can move to America and live a life of no poverty. Would you choose to stay or leave? This is the choice all people immigrating in the 1800s had to make. There are many reasons why people wanted to move to America in the 1800s. Some of them include the opportunities, freedoms, and what people can escape.     If one were to move from a country to America, one reason why they would be doing it is because of the opportunities they would gain. Firstly, they would be giving their children the opportunity to live a life free of poverty and depression. This is important because they will be happy knowing that their children will have a chance to be rich and without the knowledge of terrible things, such as homelessness. Secondly, they would be able to get a job. Unlike their country, where it is usually nearly impossible to get a job, they will be equally able to get a job as that of the person sitting next to them. Lastly, the person will be able to gain the opportunity to become rich, just like the Chinese hoped. This is important because they will be able to, just like Source #3 says, 'return proudly to China.' Not only would the person gain many opportunities, but many freedoms too.     To many people, freedom of many different things is extremely essential. This is one of the main reasons why people came to America. First of all, people would gain the freedom of religion. This is important because they will be able to practice their religious beliefs without having to worry about being punished. Second of all, they will gain the right to defend themselves in court. This is also important because in some countries, people aren't allowed to defend themselves and even if they are not guilty, they are sometimes sentenced to death. Last but not least, people will have the freedom to vote for their 'leaders.' Many people believe that it is important to be ruled by a fair leader, but when they are not able to vote, a cruel leader may come to power. People came to America in the 1800s for many reasons, one reason is because of what they can escape.     When people come to America, they not only think of the opportunities and freedoms they will gain, but also what they will escape. For example, people who live during times of war can escape to America. This is important because they will not have to worry about being killed by a bomb or weapon. Another example is that people who live with a lot of siblings and their family can't provide enough food for them can move to America. In America, there will be enough food for that person and so they won't starve to death. One last example is that the people can escape poverty. Poverty is a horrible thing. People can die of illnesses because of dirty environments. But in America, there are certain rules about living conditions, and the environment won't be as harsh.     Overall, there are many reasons why people moved to America from other countries such as the opportunites they would gain, the freedoms they would gain, and what they would escape.
